I"O<div style="background-color: #E3F4F4; padding: 15px 15px 15px 15px; border:1px solid black;">
  <b>Let \(x \in \mathbf{R}\), \(|x| \geq 0\).</b>
</div>
<p><br />
For the absolute value function definition and other properties see <a href="https://strncat.github.io/jekyll/update/2024/05/26/analysis-absolute-value-properties.html">here</a>. 
<br /></p>
<h3>Proof:</h3>
<p>By the definition of the absolute value function we have two cases:</p>
<ul>
<li>if \(x \geq 0\), then \(|x| = x\) and so \(|x| \geq 0\).</li>
<li>if \(x &lt; 0\), then \(|x| = -x\). Since \(x &lt; 0\), then \(-x &gt; 0\) so this means that \(|x| = -x &gt; 0\). As required.</li>
</ul>
<p>This second case definitely made me pause. By definition \(|x| = -x\). But \(x\) is negative. This means that \(-x\) is positive so \(|x|\) is positive!
\(\blacksquare\)
<br />
